 or Page's Amoeba Saline in 15 mL Falcon tube<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":888969,"guid":"CAB9C8B0598F11EAB021D3E6EB84A475","previous_id":888996,"previous_guid":"48ABA580599111EAB021D3E6EB84A475","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"9645CD57038B4D1CA01403187C602A79","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Plate set-up"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"F976F17B30104CD9B9FB13EE2C845FD7","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Pour PAS agar into several (3 to 5) Petri plates per 10 cells planned to isolate and let set.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":888970,"guid":"F9D2AB30598F11EAB021D3E6EB84A475","previous_id":888969,"previous_guid":"CAB9C8B0598F11EAB021D3E6EB84A475","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"A4A1CCED8C484BCCB9F43BA9F78713FB","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Plate set-up"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"98661C2B665B4BBAA0DD54EF8B51B238","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Spread 1 mL aliquot of heat-killed <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">E. coli <\/span><span>onto each plate and continue spreading until dry.<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":888996,"guid":"48ABA580599111EAB021D3E6EB84A475","previous_id":888968,"previous_guid":"B9D4D530598F11EAB021D3E6EB84A475","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"116BF6882CD64C8DB2E7995A4A19376E","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"E. coli preparation"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"674E8464AEC44DAA9C2E046FDFCAA3B8","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Heat-kill <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">E. coli <\/span><span>in 65 degree C water bath for 20 minutes.<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":889009,"guid":"A66EADB0599211EAB021D3E6EB84A475","previous_id":888970,"previous_guid":"F9D2AB30598F11EAB021D3E6EB84A475","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"4FFB1A5683F747A7AE2BAAFB8B874F54","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Plate set-up"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"944601B1FEA44D478C4E9A75E04C2533","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Scrape the internal surface of a 7 to 14 day old <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Acanthamoeba castellanii <\/span><span>liquid culture and gently shake the flask to suspend cells.<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":889039,"guid":"CCEA2E80599511EAB021D3E6EB84A475","previous_id":889009,"previous_guid":"A66EADB0599211EAB021D3E6EB84A475","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"2A21D880EC9B400C81830CB4458A1F06","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Plate set-up"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"9520A0B9B3444A7CB28892C332C4EC93","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Pipette 1 microlitre of <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Acanthamoeba <\/span><span>suspension into the centre of each plate.<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":889048,"guid":"5033E220599811EAB021D3E6EB84A475","previous_id":889039,"previous_guid":"CCEA2E80599511EAB021D3E6EB84A475","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"1D5DFC3B275445A9ACFB204E012E1B6D","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Cell isolation"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"B5B3ABBDAA474E209537ECC947F4151C","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">After 3 to 5 days, cells will have migrated far enough from the centre of the plate that the furthest ones may be 1 or more centimetres apart. Check this with an inverted microscope to determine when this is the case. There will be visible trails through the bacterial lawn to see where cells have migrated.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#84CE84","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":889049,"guid":"6E34B330599811EAB021D3E6EB84A475","previous_id":889048,"previous_guid":"5033E220599811EAB021D3E6EB84A475","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"FDDFED30D0EC42B49A6AE2F8F56BDFC6","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Cell isolation"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"0FA9968F55F14E428054F2766DDEF7EE","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">When cells have dispersed enough (1 cm or more apart), cut 1 cm squares out of the agar, containing only one cell each (not too difficult to see with an inverted microscope) and place one square into each well of a 12 well culture plate. You can cut squares from the middle of the plate into a few wells as positive controls.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#84CE84","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":889090,"guid":"7388A780599B11EAB021D3E6EB84A475","previous_id":889049,"previous_guid":"6E34B330599811EAB021D3E6EB84A475","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"966CC29AE2D142C3A132C3BD5B03FC57","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Cell isolation"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"6E4196DCC61D4E9D8C46140BD56E10BE","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Add enough PYG medium to fully cover the agar cubes (you can fully fill these wells) and allow growth at room temperature. Growth can be observed in these plates under an inverted microscope. When cells start to cover the entire area of the bottom of a well (at the same density you might see from 4-5 days growth in regular culture) you can scrape those wells and transfer the entire contents back into flasks for growth in typical culture conditions. 10 ug\/ml polymyxin B can be added to control bacterial growth in case not all <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">E. coli <\/span><span>were heat killed. If you are isolating single transformed cells you can select immediately or wait a few days to allow your new monoclonal populations to establish in your flasks.<\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#84CE84","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":null,"materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Isolation of single <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Acanthamoeba castellanii <\/span><span>cells from agar plates for establishment of monoclonal cultures. This protocol can be useful for isolating clones of a mixed wild-type population or of transformants. After isolation, growth can be re-established in typical Neff liquid medium. <\/span><\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1582834407}